[Information is scarce. When did the symptoms of the 1st and last cases first occur? When were the suspected cases reported? Is there a relationship between the cases? Did all the cases frequent the forested areas? Did they frequent the parks in which confirmed non-human primates were present? Were the discarded [cases] displaced to other localities or municipalities with transmission? For those who, according to the secretary, "lived in the north zone," what is the age group of the patients, what is the severity profile, do they all meet the current case definition criteria? In addition to vaccination, which vector control measures have been (or were) conducted in the dwelling locations (and surroundings) of the suspected cases? Additional information will be welcome.

If one or more cases are confirmed, no surprise, but much worry. - Mod.RNA

The number of cases in this area continues to increase. In October 2017, 13 parks in the area were closed to the public as a preventive measure, the great majority of them since Mon 23 Oct 2017, although authorities stated that there is no yellow fever epidemic. The increased surveillance is essential in order to detect new cases and focus the vaccination campaign. There is no indication that these human cases are due to urban, _Aedes aegypti_ transmission.

Maps of Brazil can be accessed at http://s13.postimg.org/jumnalk87/map_of_Brazil.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5435274,39294. - Mod.TY]
